/F2 13 Tf
1 0 0 1 56.0 534.0 Tm (Hold steady in three moves) Tj
/F1 10.5 Tf
1 0 0 1 66.0 517.0 Tm (1. Acknowledge: "That is a fair thing to raise.") Tj
1 0 0 1 66.0 503.0 Tm (2. Ask which kind of "expensive" it is, so you address the real one.) Tj
1 0 0 1 66.0 489.0 Tm (3. Reconnect price to the specific problem and impact they described earlier.) Tj
/F2 13 Tf
1 0 0 1 56.0 469.0 Tm (Worked example) Tj
/F1 10.5 Tf
1 0 0 1 56.0 452.0 Tm ("That is a fair thing to raise. Can I ask - is it more than you expected compared to) Tj
1 0 0 1 56.0 438.0 Tm (what you use now, or more than there is room for this quarter? ... Budget this quarter.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56.0 424.0 Tm (Understood. Earlier you said a bad coverage week costs you overtime and missed pickups -) Tj
1 0 0 1 56.0 410.0 Tm (if that is the real cost, it might be worth revisiting when budget frees up. I would) Tj
1 0 0 1 56.0 396.0 Tm (rather do that than discount into something that does not fit.") Tj
/F2 13 Tf
1 0 0 1 56.0 372.0 Tm (Safe-practice note) Tj
/F1 10.5 Tf
1 0 0 1 56.0 355.0 Tm (Do not reflexively discount to save a deal - it teaches the buyer your price is) Tj
1 0 0 1 56.0 341.0 Tm (negotiable fiction and can trap you in a bad fit. Never invent ROI figures or cite) Tj
1 0 0 1 56.0 327.0 Tm (results you cannot back up. If the value genuinely is not there for them, it is honest) Tj
1 0 0 1 56.0 313.0 Tm (to say so and step back.) Tj
